name: Se dice de mí
comments: Song composed as a milonga in 1943. The first recording was made by the Uruguayan singer Carlos Roldán with the orchestra of Francisco Canaro on May 19, 1943. The original lyrics were for a man to sing because the protagonist was a male. It is said that Tita Merello asks Pelay to change the lyrics to the song so that she could sing it, with all the burden that the theme would have, as a mockery of her own love failures. This female version achieved impressive success when it was recorded by Tita Merello with the Francisco Canaro orchestra on July 23, 1954 and included in the 1955 Argentine film Mercado de Abasto, directed by Lucas Demare.

The first recording located to date was made in 1963 by The Country Gentlemen and on their album it was credited more like a traditional song would be with just an arrangement credit by two band members, John Duffey and Pete Roberts .  However, Duffey and Roberts now do have a joint registry for their song. Mac Wiseman recorded it in 1966 and he also has a registry for his performance. name: London Bridge Is Falling Down
comments: Traditional English nursery rhyme and singing game (also known as "My Fair Lady" or "London Bridge"), which is found in different versions all over the world. It deals with the depredations of London Bridge and attempts, realistic or fanciful, to repair it. It may date back to bridge rhymes and games of the Late Middle Ages, but the earliest records of the rhyme in English are from the seventeenth century. The lyrics were first printed in close to their modern form in the mid-eighteenth century and became popular, particularly in Britain and the US during the 19th century. The most frequently used first verse is: London Bridge is falling down, Falling down, falling down. London Bridge is falling down, My fair lady.

name: Newry Town / Rude and Rambling Man / The Rambling Boy
comments: [Roud 490; Laws L12; G/D 2:260; Ballad Index LL12, CrMa161; Bodleian Roud 490; Wiltshire 782; trad.] "Newry Town" (aka "Newry Highwaymen" or "The Wild and Wicked Youth" is an Irish or English traditional highwayman song that is a plea from a condemned man to be remembered as a courageous and honourable highwayman who robbed the rich to give to the poor. The setting for this one was Newry, in the North of Ireland. The song concludes with the lines "And when I'm gone, they will tell the truth, Here lays a wild and wicked youth.” The song was Americanized into the "Rude and Rambling Man" or "The Rambling Boy" or "The Rake and Rambling Man (or Boy)".  The first US version was arranged (or arguably adapted) by Clarence Ashley of The Carolina Tar Heels as "Rude and Rambling Man". In 1941, The Carter Family recorded their more famous version called "The Rambling Boy".  A.P. Carter registered their version so it is now incorrectly thought of as a Carter Family original, but A.P. just arranged the lyrics.  The Carter Family's version starts off "I was rich but a rambling boy,  Through many cities I did enjoy...".  "The "Rake and Rambling Boy" versions just modified the opening line to - "I'm a rake and a ramblin' Boy, Well I'm a rake and ramblin' boy.  There's many a city I did enjoy...". NOTE: Not to be confused with the folk song Ramblin' Boy written by Tom Paxton.

name: Leather Britches
comments: Very popular old-time, breakdown fiddle tune in the late 1800s and well into the 1900s and derived from the late 16th century Scottish reel, Lord MacDonald's Reel The title may refer to 'leather breeches', a nickname in some parts of the American South and West for green (snap) beans dried in the pod and later cooked. Sometimes the beans would be pieced with a needle and thread and strung together, then hung to dry where they would last the winter (but would need to be soaked to re-hydrate them prior to cooking). Alternatively, the title may refer to actual garments made of leather, and it has been pointed out the the playing of the tune on the fiddle involves bowing in a motion that has been likened to the movements in sewing with a needle and thread. Many lyrical variants but a popular one went: Leather breeches full of stitches, Old shoes and stockings on-- My wife she kicked me out of bed Because I had my breeches on.
